item.description:
Enzyme is invoked by calling a function __enzyme_autodiff with the function being differentiated, followed by the corresponding primal and shadow arguments. This will result in the original function being run with the corresponding derivative values being computed.
Function Hooks Enzyme replaces all calls to functions that contain the string __enzyme_autodiff with a call to the corresponding derivative. This is done to allow Enzyme to register multiple function signatures.
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;template&lt;typename T&gt; T square(T x) { return x * x; } float __enzyme_autodiffFloat(float (*)(float), float); double __enzyme_autodiffDouble(double (*)(double), double); int main() { printf(&#34;float d/dx %f\n&#34;, __enzyme_autodiffFloat(square&lt;float&gt;, 1.
